<subSubSection pageId="299" pageNumber="300" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="299" pageNumber="300">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="299" pageNumber="300">
This Holarctic species ranges from Scandinavia (Balkenohl 2003: 226) to the Hudson Bay in northeastern Manitoba (Garry 1993: 94, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1844" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Dyschirius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="299" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigricornis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="299" pageNumber="300">Dyschirius nigricornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Fossil remnants, dated between 10,800 and 20,530 years B.P., have been unearthed in central North Dakota (Ashworth and Schwert 1992: 260), northeastern Iowa (Schwert 1992: 76; Woodman et al. 1996: 17), and southeastern Iowa (Baker et al. 1986: 96).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
